default3.1 
defaultThe Chair of the Committee, Louise Ellman MP, has 
defaultsaid :-
default “People from different communities across the UK should have access to adequate transport services. We will be looking at how best to meet the needs of passengers in isolated communities, including rural areas, island communities, and suburban or urban areas with poor transport connections”.
default&#xa0;
default3.2 
defaultIn August 2006 TWNW published 
defaultits 
defaultstudy of Rural Transport Funding. We believe the Committee may find it helpful to visit 
default this as it complements much of our submission.
default&#xa0;
default3.3 
defaultRising relative prosperity and consequential increased car ownership post World War II created a Rural Transport Problem which by the time of the 
defaultBeeching
default 
default rail closures was beginning to stir the Nation’s conscience.
default&#xa0;
default3.4 T
defaulthe then Government responded by creating a committee chaired by Prof
defaultessor
default Jack 
default which found that public transport in rural areas was essentially 
defaultunremunerative
default and thus, in today’s terms, non-commercial and proposed providing a subsidy in the form of a rebate of the tax paid by the operators in providing rural services 
default. It also discovered that the suggestion most frequently made to them of Minibuses providing rural services was “by no means a universal panacea”
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.5 
defaultBy the time PTEs and Local Transport Authorities (LTAs) were created 
defaultby the Transport Act 1
default968 all “stage carriage” 
default services qualified for Fuel Duty Rebate 
default(FDR) 
defaultwhich became the default support mechanism for rural transport services, and also increasingly, as this consultation exercise obviously recognises, for services in similarly isolated communities. Off Peak 
defaultSunday  and
default evening services in many suburbs and small towns are now only marginally commercial by virtue of the F
defaultDR 
defaultfor which they still qualify. 
default&#xa0;
default3.6 
defaultIt was recognised that deregulation of the bus industry 
default(under the Transport Act 1985) 
defaultcould deprive rural services of any cross subsidy from licensed commercial services and thus financial support over and above FDR might be called for. The 1985 Act created a Rural Transport Development Fund (RTDF), administered by the Rural Development Commission (RDG) and later by the Countryside Agency (
defaultCoAg
default) 
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.7 
defaultOne of the beneficiaries of RTDF was Royal Mail, who in the late 1980’s significantly grew their network of Post Buses. This was at the peak of an ill
default-
default fated parallel and mainly urban commercial “minibus revolution”. Few commercial minibuses or Post Buses survive today!
default&#xa0;
default3.8 
defaultWhen the Coalition Government disposed of 
defaultCoAg
default  in
default 2011 
default  the professional skills of their officers and partners 
default were lost (see question 1). A (formula based) Rural Bus Grant and a Rural Transport Challenge (for which operators or procurers had to bid) were carried forward but only for the short term, and are now defunct, “replaced” by non
default-
defaultrural
default-
defaultspecific Better Bus Areas (BBAs) and Local Sustainable Transport Funds (LSTF). Bus operators currently appear far more concerned about the future of BSOG which is fast being decoupled from Fuel Duty.
default&#xa0;
default3.9 
defaultTWNW concluded in its 2006 report 
default that where rural transport funding is limited to 
defaultc
defaultapital expenditure it is generally sub optimal, since operators require long term 
defaultr
defaultevenue funding if non
default-
defaultcommercial services are to be protected. The report noted the revenue implications of capital spending and proposed the mainstreaming of 
defaultr
defaultevenue funding.
default&#xa0;
default3.10 
defaultT
defaultW
defaultNW note
defaults
default that the Committee 
defaultis
default particularly interested in the provision of bus and rail services, as well as the role of Community Transport services”.
default&#xa0;
default3.11 
defaultBy definition
default 
default Community Transport 
default(CT) 
defaultis not public transport, although Community Buses can be. Rural Communities have a long tradition both of offering lifts to neighbours and of car sharing. It was the legalisation 
default of car sharing for a (non
default-
defaultcommercial)
default 
default“fare” (sufficient only to recover operating costs) which encouraged the development of 
defaultCT  
default. The sector has expanded greatly in the last 
defaulttwo
default years, with some large social enterprises prepared to tender for marginal services in areas of low 
defaultdemand
default 
default. It was pleasing to note the easements made by the Local Transport Act 2008 to assist operators of small passenger carrying vehicles (including taxis) wishing to provide (or reinstate) marginal registered local services 
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.12 
defaultThe Association of Community Rail Partnerships 
default(ACORP) 
defaulthas succeeded in facilitating bus/rail co-ordination at a few rural stations, some of which have also participated in parallel ACORP station adoption schemes. 
defaultHowever 
defaultin most instances a lack of co-ordination between bus and rail transport is 
defaultstill 
defaultthe rule rather than the exception with many bus services not serving the village/town stations, and
default,
default where they do
default,
default not connecting 
defaultwell 
defaultwith each other
default’
defaults services. Better co-ordination would enable a station to serve many surrounding villages. In some cases the rail service provided does not tie in with local needs - e.g. 
defaultthe 
defaultLancaster - Leeds service does not allow commuting from the 
defaultLancs
default/Craven villages to either destination thus minimising rural job opportunities. We should also not forget the need for rural station car parks which allow rural access to public transport into towns and cities - historic land sales have removed practical parking facilities from many rural stations.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne of the problems of buses serving rail stations is that 
defaultadditional travel time 
defaultcan be caused to 
defaultpassengers not using th
defaulte station.
