default4.13 
defaultPublic Transport services in all areas, but especially
default defaultin isolated and rural areas, generate significant cross sector benefits. For example, old persons’ domiciliary care may be reduced by the provision of a service which allows them to shop independently rather than rely on their home help,
default 
defaultwith subsequent cost savings for the taxpayer. The cost of the help and the benefits to 
defaultthe elderly 
defaultof their consequential
default 
defaultimproved mental health and independence are rarely, if ever, passed to the procurer of that service.
default 
defaultTWNW has always argued that the LTAs should be able to capture these cross sector benefits.
default&#xa0;
default4.14 
defaultLTAs can do much to encourage the establishment of brokerages between the social enterprises they support, so that better utilisation can be made of the many small buses operated by their social services, the NHS’s Patient Transport Services, schools within their control and voluntary and other bodies. 
defaultIndeed there is a duty under Section 88 of the 1985 Act
default to 
defaultco-operate which could include a
defaultrrang
defaulting 
defaultbrokerages as a way of extracting value for money from all forms of public
default 
defaultsupported transport services
default.
default 
defaultNot all CT Social Enterprises are entirely Community Bus based, some of the larger ones have branched out beyond the provision of Community Buses with success in operating tendered bus services and even preserved 
defaultrailways 
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default6. To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?default&#xa0;
default4.15 
defaultA reliable bus or rail service is generally preferred to demand responsive transport which can either be not available to the public at large or require potential users to pre-register and pre-book. However DRT can be designed 
defaultto operate more efficiently and at less cost than Registered Local Services and should be supported where no obvious alternatives exist. Given that the usually low volume of passengers is such that a regular service by time or day is unlikely to be best value for money flexible journeys tailored to passenger 
defaultneed can
default 
defaultoften 
defaultbe 
defaultmore appropriate.
default&#xa0;
default4.16 
defaultIn such cases the LTA might be encouraged (or required) to fund 
default the operator to accept concessionary passes and/or to subsidise a lower fare but this does raise issues about passenger commitment for a specially purchased service which L
defaultT
defaultA's need the power to deal with where there is abuse of the service.
default&#xa0;
default4.17 
defaultTWNW has already recently given evidence 
default to the committee on the potential for using taxis at separate fares to replace some marginal services.
default&#xa0;
default7. What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?default&#xa0;
default4.18 
defaultBus and rail fares are a critical consideration when discussing public transport in isolated areas where demand is low. Whilst rail fares are regulated, bus fares generally
default are
default 
defaultnot 
default, so it can often be cheaper to make the same trip by train than by bus in rural areas. Station to station rail fares are readily available but bus fares are hard to ascertain in advance of 
defaulttravel 
default. 
default&#xa0;
default4.19 
defaultThe advent of 
defaultconcessionary traveldefault has undoubtedly grown ridership (a goal of the last Government) but obviously cannot do so in places where there are no bus services. Operators and LTAs each cite market distortions and arbitrary disbursement regimes. It is not unusual for 
defaultLTAs  to
default use discretionary powers to extend concessionary travel to DR
defaultT
default, C
defaultT
default and local rail services. 
defaultHowever whilst some LTA's may allow use on rail this is a rarity in rural areas.
default This leaves pass holders in the country doubly disadvantaged with 
defaultfewer
default services and many they cannot use. In some area the only bus is the school bus and the late start of concession allowance sometimes means these cannot be used either.
default 
defaultL
defaultT
defaultA’s 
defaultshould be 
defaultmore understanding in allowing special case use by local
default people
default of rail services
default, though we recognise that there are cost implications
default.  
default&#xa0;
default4.20 
defaultTravel is highly price sensitive and on the supply side fares will reflect, 
defaultinter
default 
defaultalia
default, amounts of subsidy received. There could be a case, therefore, for some degree of re-regulation of fares, especially in rural areas where often there is 
defaulta
default monopoly of one operator offering no choice.
default&#xa0;
default4.21 
defaultHowever there is some degree of control 
default over competition and this can have unintended consequences, such as preventing subsidised rural services from picking up or setting down along parts of their route where  competition with either tendered or commercial service(s) might arise. The introduction of multi operator ticketing would be helpful in reducing these consequences.
